latestPosts.caption:
Clear skin isn’t just topical- it’s a reflection of how you’re living.
Breakouts start showing up because of the little habits we aren’t even noticing- dirty brushes, skipping sleep, too much sugar or just over-cleansing.
Once you start  paying attention to what is happening outside of your skincare routine, things begin to shift.

•Not washing makeup brushes weekly
Brushes collect leftover makeup, oil and bacteria. If you keep reusing them without cleaning, you’re basically pressing that buildup back into your skin- leading to clogged pores and breakouts.

•Not rinsing after micellar water
Micellar water can leave behind a film of residue and cleansing agents. If you don’t rinse it off, it can clog pores and irritate your skin especially if you layer other products right after.

•Caffeine on an empty stomach
Coffee first thing in the morning can spike cortisol (your stress hormone), irritate your gut, and throw off your hormones, which all show up on your face. Especially for acne-prone skin, this can be a trigger.

•Not eating a wholesome, balanced diet
Your skin reflects what’s happening inside. If your meals lack variety- especially protein, healthy fats, and micronutrients- your skin might not get the building blocks it needs to heal, glow and stay balanced. A diet rich in whole foods supports both your gut and hormones, which are key for clear skin.

•Too much sugar
Sugar increases insulin, which can trigger oil production and inflammation. Over time, it can also lead to something called glycation- which damages collagen and makes acne worse.

•Inconsistent sleep
When you’re not sleeping well or getting enough rest, your body can’t repair your skin properly. Hormones also get thrown off and inflammation increases- which can cause or worsen acne.

#clearskin #clearskintips #acneproneskin #acnetreatment #skingoals #acnepositivity #acnetips #acne #skincare #skincaretips

I’ve been dealing with hormonal acne since December and waking up to new breakouts every morning was tough. But after making these changes to my routine, my skin started to clear. It wasn’t easy but it worked. If you’re struggling with the same thing, I hope this helps - even a little!

1-Eat 2 Brazil Nuts Daily - They’re rich in selenium, a powerful antioxidant that reduces inflammation, supports thyroid function and helps balance hormones - key for keeping breakouts in check.

2-Balance Your Meals - Sounds easy but let’s be real- it’s not always possible. Skipping meals, eating too many processed carbs or not getting enough protein can spike blood sugar and lead to hormonal imbalances (hello, acne). Aim for a mix of protein, fiber, healthy fats, and carbs to keep hormones stable and skin happy.

3- Sync Your Workouts to Your Cycle - Intense workouts at the wrong time can spike cortisol (stress hormone) worsening breakouts. Instead:
	•	Follicular phase (days 1-14): Higher energy? Strength train or do HIIT.
	•	Luteal phase (days 15-28): Feeling sluggish? Stick to walks, pilates, or yoga.
	•	This helps reduce stress, supports with hormone balance and keeps skin clear.

4- Spearmint Tea - Studies show it helps lower androgens (hormones that trigger oil production and breakouts). A cup a day can make a difference!

5- Manage Stress Daily - Chronic stress = cortisol spikes = hormonal imbalance = acne. Try meditation, deep breathing or yoga to keep stress in check. 

6- Stay Hydrated - Water supports detoxification, digestion and overall skin health. Dehydration can lead to excess oil production, making acne worse.

Small changes, big results!

 #HormonalAcne #ClearSkin #acne #acnepositivity #hormones
